  "citations": [
    {
      "code": "3.75(c)(1)(ii)",
      "kind": "",
      "repeat": false,
      "desc": "Housing facilities, general.",
      "narrative": "The metal shelter in the enclosure containing 2 brown lemurs had a long tear where the floor joins the front wall. There\nwas a strip of metal hanging from the corner. This creates an unstable floor surface in the shelter and the tear may have\njagged or sharp edges. There is a strip of metal hanging from the floor that could also have sharp edges.\nFurniture-type fixtures or objects must be sturdily constructed and must be strong enough to provide the safe activity and\nwelfare of nonhuman primates. Any surfaces that come in contact with nonhuman primates must be free of jagged edges\nor sharp points that might injure the animals. The licensee must provide a shelter that is intact and structurally sound at all\ntimes.\nTo be corrected by: 14 March 2026"
    },
    {
      "code": "3.75(e)",
      "kind": "",
      "repeat": false,
      "desc": "Housing facilities, general.",
      "narrative": "Inside the marmoset house was a storage cupboard with treats and other supplies. On the shelf was an open box of\nCheerios that had debris from insects around the box on the shelf and inside the open bag inside the box. Insects can\ncontaminate the food which can then cause illness in the animals.\nSupplies of food and bedding must be stored in a manner that protects the supplies from spoilage, contamination, and\nvermin infestation. Only the food and bedding currently being used may be kept in animal areas, and when not in actual\nuse, open food and bedding supplies must be kept in leakproof containers with tightly fitting lids to prevent spoilage and\ncontamination\nThe licensee must remove the contaminated food. Any opened food container must be kept in leakproof containers with\ntightly fitting lids.\nTo be corrected by: 14 March 2026\nThis inspection and exit interview were conducted with facility representative.\nn"
    }
  ],
  "narrative": "3.75(c)(1)(ii) \n   \nHousing facilities, general. \nThe metal shelter in the enclosure containing 2 brown lemurs had a long tear where the floor joins the front wall. There \nwas a strip of metal hanging from the corner. This creates an unstable floor surface in the shelter and the tear may have \njagged or sharp edges. There is a strip of metal hanging from the floor that could also have sharp edges.  \n \nFurniture-type fixtures or objects must be sturdily constructed and must be strong enough to provide the safe activity and \nwelfare of nonhuman primates. Any surfaces that come in contact with nonhuman primates must be free of jagged edges \nor sharp points that might injure the animals. The licensee must provide a shelter that is intact and structurally sound at all \ntimes.  \n \nTo be corrected by: 14 March 2026 \n3.75(e) \n   \nHousing facilities, general. \nInside the marmoset house was a storage cupboard with treats and other supplies. On the shelf was an open box of \nCheerios that had debris from insects around the box on the shelf and inside the open bag inside the box. Insects can \ncontaminate the food which can then cause illness in the animals.  \nSupplies of food and bedding must be stored in a manner that protects the supplies from spoilage, contamination, and \nvermin infestation. Only the food and bedding currently being used may be kept in animal areas, and when not in actual \nuse, open food and bedding supplies must be kept in leakproof containers with tightly fitting lids to prevent spoilage and \ncontamination \nThe licensee must remove the contaminated food. Any opened food container must be kept in leakproof containers with \ntightly fitting lids. \n \nTo be corrected by: 14 March 2026 \n \nThis inspection and exit interview were conducted with facility representative.\n\nn",
